# --- LLM Artifacts for the RuleSet ---

gumshoe:LLM_RuleSetOverview a rpg:LLMArtifact ;
    rpg:artifactType rpg:SystemPrompt ;
    rpg:artifactAppliesTo gumshoe:GUMSHOE_SRD ;
    rpg:artifactFormat "markdown" ;
    rpg:artifactLanguage "en" ;
    rpg:artifactText """# GUMSHOE System Reference Document — LLM Guide

## Core Principle
GUMSHOE is an investigation-focused RPG. The central question is NOT "will the heroes get the information?" but "what will the heroes DO with the information once they've got it?"

## Two Ability Systems
- **Investigative Abilities**: NEVER require a die roll. If a PC has a relevant ability at rating 1+, they automatically get core clues. Spending pool points yields special benefits (extra info, narrative advantages).
- **General Abilities**: Use 1d6 + pool spend vs Difficulty Number. These introduce uncertainty and risk. Used for physical actions, combat, survival.

## Key Mechanics
- **Rating**: Static value, purchased with build points. Represents baseline competence.
- **Pool**: Dynamic resource starting equal to rating each case. Spent during play for bonuses and special benefits.
- **Tests**: 1d6 + spent points >= Difficulty Number (usually 4). Only for General abilities.
- **Contests**: Alternating tests until one side fails.
- **Spends**: Paying pool points for investigative special benefits (1-2 points typically).

## Combat
- Uses Scuffling (melee) or Shooting (ranged) as contested abilities.
- Hit Threshold: 3 (or 4 if Athletics 8+). Opponent must meet/beat to hit.
- Damage = 1d6 + weapon modifier. Subtracted from Health pool.
- Health below 0: consciousness rolls, serious wounds, death at -12.

## Stability
- Mental resilience tracker. Failed Stability tests lose points.
- Shaken (0 to -5), Mental Illness (-6 to -11), Incurably Insane (-12-).

## Scenario Design
- Built around trails of clues: investigation trigger → sinister conspiracy → trail of clues.
- Core clues are ALWAYS available. Never gate story progress behind die rolls.
- Scene types: Introductory, Core, Alternate, Antagonist Reaction, Hazard, Sub-Plot, Conclusion.
- Clue types: Core, Floating Core, Leveraged, Pipe, Restricted, Timed Result.
""" .

gumshoe:LLM_CorePhilosophy a rpg:LLMArtifact ;
    rpg:artifactType rpg:StyleGuide ;
    rpg:artifactAppliesTo gumshoe:GUMSHOE_SRD ;
    rpg:artifactFormat "markdown" ;
    rpg:artifactLanguage "en" ;
    rpg:artifactText """# GUMSHOE Design Philosophy for GMs and AI Assistants

## Never Withhold Core Clues
If a PC has the right ability and is in the right place, they get the clue. Period. No roll required. This is the single most important rule in GUMSHOE.

## Failure Is Not Interesting for Information Gathering
In source fiction (CSI, Sherlock Holmes), investigators don't fail to use their expertise. The drama comes AFTER the clues are found, during interpretation and action.

## Spends Are Spotlight Moments
When a player spends investigative pool points, they're buying a moment of cool competence. Reward this with vivid, useful, character-affirming information.

## General Ability Tests Create Suspense
Reserve tests for dramatically important moments. Most general ability uses should succeed automatically. Tests introduce genuine risk.

## The GM Never Reveals Difficulty Numbers
Players must decide blind how many points to commit. This creates tension and meaningful resource management.

## Elastic Participation
Assume all PCs are sort-of present in every scene unless it would be absurd. Don't get bogged down in logistics of who went where.

## Follow the Players
If players invest in a theory, consider adapting rather than negating. Make them half-right. Build twists on their contributions. Never negate.
""" .

